/COMMIT_MSG.message:
Hi Ifat!
a. That's good to know. As Anusha and I have been discussing in another comment, we can also add in the near future the ability to remove all rows fitting some criteria. Something like:
  {
    "op":"remove",
    "criteria":{
      "state":"active",
      "severity":1
    }
  }
This would allow removal by ID. Would that work well for vitrage?

1. That's probably something we have to figure out together. And whatever makes the most sense can be implemented in the congress notifier in vitrage. Do you have a sense of a typical high-end number of alarms including deactivated ones?

2. The semantics of the PATCH call is that all the operations passed in are applied in order, and then only the final result is sent to the policy engine. So the semantics of remove+add in the same PATCH call is exactly the same as the semantics of update. I think that alleviates the concern right?

Hi Ifat,

Update makes sense, but it seems simplest from a protocol perspective to simply express an update as a remove+add.

For example,
{"op":"replace",
 "before-value": {"id":"1-1", "name":"name1", "state":"active", "severity":1},
 "after-value": {"id":"1-1", "name":"name1", "state":"inactive", "severity":1}
}

May as well be expressed as:
[
{"op":"remove",
 "value": {"id":"1-1", "name":"name1", "state":"active", "severity":1}
},
{"op":"add",
 "value": {"id":"1-1", "name":"name1", "state":"inactive", "severity":1}
}
]

The main question is whether vitrage has all the information to specify all the fields of the row to remove and the row to add. If it does, then keeping the protocol simple for now seems best.

But if vitrage does not have all the information readily available (we discussed this over ML a bit), then we can think about more advanced operations that update just a specific field of a row without specifying the whole row.

The basic model is that each table is a set of rows, and the source can add/remove a row to/from the set. So in the basic form, we ask the row be completely specified for removal from the set. Keep in mind that currently congress does not treat the column 'id' as special. And a table does not have to have the 'id' column.

In an extension, it could make sense for us to allow removal of rows with incomplete specification. For example, we could allow a body like the following to remove all rows where state is active and severity is 1.
  {
    "op":"remove",
    "criteria":{
      "state":"active",
      "severity":1
    }
  }

We probably want to keep this remove by criteria distinct from the remove by (fully specified) value because otherwise it's way too easy for a bad remove-by-value call to unintentionally remove a bunch of rows.

